00:04:14.905 --> 00:04:19.315
The OpenShift CI and CD
integrate with Jenkins,

106
00:04:19.315 --> 00:04:22.720
while the Kubernetes CI
and CD can be integrated,

107
00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:25.020
but not with Jenkins.

108
00:04:25.020 --> 00:04:28.660
OpenShift runs on top of
a Kubernetes cluster,

109
00:04:28.660 --> 00:04:33.100
with object data stored in
the etcd key-value store.

110
00:04:33.100 --> 00:04:36.210
It has a microservices-based
architecture.

111
00:04:36.210 --> 00:04:39.590
Its services are REST APIs,

112
00:04:39.590 --> 00:04:43.090
which expose the core
objects, and controllers,

113
00:04:43.090 --> 00:04:45.090
which read the REST APIs,

114
00:04:45.090 --> 00:04:47.390
apply changes to
the other objects,

115
00:04:47.390 --> 00:04:50.570
and report status or
write back to the object.

116
00:04:50.570 --> 00:04:53.650
They also maintain the
cluster desired state.

117
00:04:53.650 --> 00:04:56.250
Docker provides abstraction
for packaging and

118
00:04:56.250 --> 00:04:59.730
creating Linux-based
lightweight container images.

119
00:04:59.730 --> 00:05:02.190
Kubernetes provides
cluster management

120
00:05:02.190 --> 00:05:05.200
and orchestrates containers
on multiple hosts.

121
00:05:05.200 --> 00:05:09.150
OpenShift features add
management of source code,

122
00:05:09.150 --> 00:05:11.690
builds, and deployments
for developers,

123
00:05:11.690 --> 00:05:13.610
managing and promoting images

124
00:05:13.610 --> 00:05:15.950
at scale as they flow
through your system,

125
00:05:15.950 --> 00:05:18.390
application management at scale,

126
00:05:18.390 --> 00:05:20.530
team and user
tracking management

127
00:05:20.530 --> 00:05:22.770
of a large developer
organization,

128
00:05:22.770 --> 00:05:26.910
and networking infrastructure
that supports the cluster.

